
Question:    What is Type Casting?
Answer:
Type casting means converting one data type into another.  
Example: converting an int to double, or a double to int.  


There are 3 types of Type Casting in C#:


1) Implicit Casting (Automatic)

      •   Performed automatically by the compiler           
      •   Converts smaller data types to larger data types   
      •   No data loss occurs                                
      •   No special syntax is needed                        
      •   Safe and simple                                    
      •   Happens in order:  char → int → long → float → double  

      Example:                                                
            int a = 9;                                        
            double b = a;         // b = 9.0                  



2) Explicit Casting (Manual)

      •   Done manually by the programmer                    
      •   Converts larger data types to smaller data types    
      •   May cause data loss                                 
      •   Uses (type) before the value                        
      •   Useful when you're sure about the conversion        

      Example:                                                
            double a = 9.78;                                  
            int b = (int)a;      // b = 9                     



3) Using Convert Class

      •   Uses built-in methods to convert between types      
      •   Can handle null and default values safely           
      •   Works with strings, numbers, booleans, etc.         
      •   Provides readable and reusable code                

      Common Methods:                                         
            Convert.ToString()                                
            Convert.ToDouble()                                
            Convert.ToInt32()                                 
            Convert.ToBoolean()                               

      Example:                                                
            int a = 10;                                       
            double b = 5.25;                                  
            bool c = true;                                    

            Console.WriteLine(Convert.ToString(a));       // "10"
            Console.WriteLine(Convert.ToDouble(a));       // 10.0
            Console.WriteLine(Convert.ToInt32(b));        // 5
            Console.WriteLine(Convert.ToString(c));       // "True"

